There is one primary aspect that I appreciate about @bohoboco.perfume :

Clarity. The concepts for their fragrances are crystal clear. Not only in terms of the unusual combinations of main ingredients featured in each fragrance, but also the very thoughtful write-ups behind them.

They are seeking to tell stories, and convey sentiments. 

All that being said, I don’t absolutely love all of the offerings of theirs that I’ve tried, and of the four bottles you see here (provided to me by the brand), I truly enjoy one of them with two of them growing on me.

All of their perfumes are extremely potent—very long lasting with dense, persistent profiles. I think this might actually detract from my enjoyment of some of them. They overwhelm me a bit at times. 

But this is just personal preference—some of you seek this, and you’ll find it here. 😆

Wet Cherry Liquor is objectively pleasant, but unfortunately reminds me of a cough syrup I often took as a kid, so subjective negative association is afflicting my experience with it. 

Wild Carrot Oud is one of the strangest profiles I’ve smelled in a long time. I don’t hate it but I don’t necessarily like it either—I’m intrigued by it, and it is growing on me. It smells like earthy, bittersweet, spiced warm carrot cake. I appreciate its uniqueness, so I will give it some time.

Eternal Lily Amber is a beautiful and unique profile—crispy Granny Smith apple surrounded by thick florals and underscored by a warm and creamy vanilla. For me, this is the one whose profile unfortunately puts me off a little because of its strength.

Jasmine White Leather is opulent, almost delicious-smelling vanillic-jasmine that almost resembles white chocolate to me, with a smooth leathery base. It was almost too much for me for the first few hours, but the dry down is what won me over. It becomes  intoxicating.

I recently started using a categorization system that is simple and can be easily applied to just about any video concept.

I’m using three broad levels of fragrance collection/experience to explain my recommendations:

1️⃣ Starting- perhaps you’ve been following fragrance reviewers and building your collection for up to a year now. You’re still quite bright-eyed and bushy-tailed, and you’re very excited about new ways to smell good!

2️⃣ Intrigued- the mainstream realm is beginning to be less appealing. You still enjoy some of the fragrances you have, but they no longer excite you. You are interested in more interesting options.

3️⃣ Enthusiast- while your mainstream fragrances may still have function in your collection, they might occupy a minority of your fragrance wearing. You are looking for new scent experiences, and might even have a growing interest in the artistry behind perfumery.

Today’s video highlights what a small fragrance collection for each level could look like, with some tips scattered throughout!

Discovering new fragrances is very exciting.

I have had almost 1,000 bottles pass through my collection since I started in this hobby, and I’ve learned so much by smelling so much.

But here’s the part that sucks: your early loves being forgotten. Wasting away.

They sit untouched, collecting dust, as new scents come into your sphere and seize your attention. 

It’s not that your love for your older scents wanes, it’s that you only have so much bandwidth to spend time with them as new ones integrate. 

In the past, this has been cause for me to get rid of many, many fragrances. I am not one who enjoys having excess—it is often overwhelming. 

I sometimes envy those who have maybe 15 or fewer fragrances that they absolutely love. But having a large library of scents is the current reality of a credible fragrance reviewer, and I accept it. 

But don’t get me wrong—I love my collection and it brings me much joy.

Let me know how you feel about this. 👇🏾

I’ve been sitting on NFT 1 from @scentsofwood for some time now. 

And by sitting, I don’t mean sitting. Look at that cap. Ouch. 😖 I mean discovering. 😆

I’ve spent the past few months getting to know this very simple, yet mysterious fragrance, masterfully perfumed by @pascalgaurinperfumer 

In essence, it is a woody fragrance enshrouded in a slightly sweet musk. But what brings it to this conclusion is a bit more than that. 

I can detect the familiar, slightly bitter woodiness of Vetiver at the heart of this scent, but it is freshened by lavender, geranium, and spicy cardamom. 

Don’t be fooled by what I just said—these elements do not stand beside one another on a platter. They are truly blended into an accord, and I believe that the musky element is to thank for this. 

It envelops everything in a dense, yet translucent fog—you can smell hints of the aforementioned facets almost as stand-alone ingredients for brief moments, until they are pulled back into the fog. 

It is amazing how something so simple can be so captivating.

As NFT 1 sits on my skin, I can feel a grounding and almost ambery warmth balancing the fresh musk and woods. I believe the cistus is to thank for that.

All in all, this is a scent personality that leaves itself to be discovered, yet it persists. It will meld with your own chemistry, and as a result, even for having quite an overdose of aroma chemicals, smells incredibly natural.

Today’s video is not what everyone will want to hear.

Resisting instant gratification in the fragrance consumer/influencer space is quite a feat. But if you can do it, I think it will only yield fulfillment and stave off headache. 

It is very easy to say, “I tried this fragrance and loved it, but it’s too expensive. Are there any cheaper alternatives?”

Is this harmless? Definitely. But you know what is also harmless? Saving your pennies until you can afford that thing you already know you love.

I didn’t mention this in the video, but clones often don’t convey the same magic as the original. So you’re likely selling yourself short by giving into impatience and buying early.

If you feel averse to any of my points in the video, I totally understand. Nonetheless, I hope we can have a mature and logical discussion about it without letting emotion get involved.

We’re back with a critical analysis of another highly-discussed facet of fragrance-wearing: performance.

In a nutshell, performance is ultimately a subjective variable with fragrances. It can be controlled by the perfumer to some degree, but variability among experiences CANNOT be controlled.

Because of this, I believe that judging a fragrance based on its performance is not always an accurate representation. Why? Because WE are the variable. We seldom consider ourselves when experiencing “poor” performance from a fragrance, and instead place all of the blame on the liquid in the pretty bottle. 🫠

It is beyond exhausting to see folks saying, “it’s not good because it doesn’t last”, rather than “unfortunately it doesn’t seem to last on ME, but I understand it could be different for others” (or something to that effect).

I’m rambling—I hope you enjoy the full video, and I’d love to know what you think. The link is in my bio 👌🏾

So let’s shift our mindset a bit—instead of treating a fragrance like a product that is supposed to function a specific way, like a car, treat it as an extension of you. As soon as it leaves the bottle, it becomes invisible. It becomes a part of you, and you become the product. 👌🏾
.
.
The opposite of this would be only spraying fabric or paper, and simply carrying it with you so that the scent follows you…but you could put the object down at any time and the scent is no longer associated with your presence. 👌🏾

I don’t know about you, but I’m glad it’s not this way. So let’s stop treating fragrance like a performance product—you’ll be disappointed most of the time you do this. You and your sense of smell are the product. 👌🏾
